{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585125","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585125"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:03:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:03:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14870"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14870"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.44,0.21,0,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7561"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115393"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7561"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14870"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97396"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"5440"},{"type":"tags","id":"7881"},{"type":"tags","id":"8111"},{"type":"tags","id":"8545"},{"type":"tags","id":"9979"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18491"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18539"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115393","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115393"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDendritic cells are professional antigen-presenting cells that play a crucial role in initiating and regulating immune responses. Different types are found in specific anatomical locations.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the dendritic cells located in the T cell areas of lymph nodes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Langerhans cells","Follicular dendritic cells","Interdigitating dendritic cells","Plasmacytoid dendritic cells","Myeloid dendritic cells"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Einterdigitating dendritic cells\u003C/strong\u003E, which are found in T cell zones (paracortex) of lymph nodes where they present processed antigens to T cells. Their name comes from their long membrane processes that interweave between T cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELangerhans cells\u003C/strong\u003E are specialized dendritic cells found in the epidermis of skin and mucous membranes. \u003Cstrong\u003EFollicular dendritic cells\u003C/strong\u003E are found in B cell follicles where they present intact antigens to B cells. \u003Cstrong\u003EPlasmacytoid dendritic cells\u003C/strong\u003E are circulating cells that produce large amounts of type I interferons in response to viral infection. \u003Cstrong\u003EMyeloid dendritic cells\u003C/strong\u003E are a broader category of conventional dendritic cells found in various tissues. Each type of dendritic cell has specific locations and functions in the immune system, making them crucial for both innate and adaptive immunity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Interdigitating dendritic cells are found in T cell areas (paracortex) of lymph nodes where they present processed antigens to T lymphocytes","Langerhans cells are dendritic cells found in the epidermis of skin and mucous membranes","Follicular dendritic cells are located in B cell follicles and present intact antigens to B cells"],"references":["Tigner A, Ibrahim SA, Murray IV. Histology, White Blood Cell. [Updated 2022 Nov 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK563148/","Playfair, J. H. L., \u0026 Chain, B. M. (2012). Immunology at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Nauseef WM, Borregaard N. Neutrophils at work. Nat Immunol. 2014 Jul;15(7):602-11. doi: 10.1038/ni.2921. PMID: 24940954"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97396"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14870"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97396"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T14:42:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T14:42:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7561"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115393"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4936"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immune System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"positio